      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate ASTM F1717 protocol; multiple loading rates or environmental conditions evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed strictly per ASTM F1717 at a single quasi-static loading rate (5 mm/min) and ambient laboratory conditions. Only one test condition was evaluated; no variation in loading rate or simulated physiological environment was included. Achieved level (2) is below required level (3), representing a known gap acknowledged in the overall credibility determination."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to test article parameters; mapping documented.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping each FEA input to the corresponding measured or specified test article parameter. CMM-measured dimensions were used directly in the FEA geometry. Material properties were matched to the certified test reports for the production lot. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture constraints as verified by fixture drawing review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using relative difference and E/uval metric; all QoIs within acceptance bounds.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) were compared quantitatively using relative percent difference and the normalized validation metric E/uval. All three QoIs satisfied the pre-specified acceptance bounds (<10% relative difference; E/uval < 1.96) across both laboratories. Results are summarized in the validation result records."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory decision criteria.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load transfer to adjacent vertebrae; yield force is the primary failure criterion for screw fracture risk; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption. All three QoIs are specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly relevant to the regulatory decision regarding pedicle screw mechanical performance. QoI relevance is high."
    },
